              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">How To Be A Turtle</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2288"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2288"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=55">Nick "JediBrain" Stefanko</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 55 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">A path to establishing control over your Star Wars CCG games you play.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Introduction:<br>
<br>
I may know what you&#146;re thinking: &quot;What does a turtle have to do with Star Wars CCG?&quot;  Everything, my friend.  Turtling, as I have come to interpret it and will use thusly for this entire article, is the style of play used with certain deck types to take full mental control of the game.  This may make you think: &quot;But I have a winning deck that I like; I am in control of all my games.&quot;  Sorry to disappoint, but you are wrong.<br>
In today&#146;s current meta, fast gameplay is revered.  The &#146;better&#146; deck is always assumed to be the fastest.  The problem I find with such fast decks is both the opportunity for mistake and the unpredictability of the game.  Despite being interpreted as fun and exciting, no one has mental control of the game.  Play proceeds as a means to best the opponent physically on the table.  I prefer the more insidious approach of frustrating, confounding, and ruining my opponent.<br>
<br>
The Key:<br>
<br>
The key to turtling is the deck you play.  There are very, very few decks you can turtle effectively with.  For the purposes of this article and allowing you some self-discovery, I will focus on two deck types: Mind What You Have Learned and Commence Primary Ignition.  You may see MWYHL as the obvious choice for Light Side, but couldn&#146;t see CPI coming at you for Dark.<br>
<br>
How To:<br>
<br>
The concept of turtling is to outwit your opponent and to ignore him/her until you are ready to deal with them (don&#146;t assume I&#146;m speaking in terms of a mains-and-toys style deck, where you wait for your opponent to make the first move; I mean let your opponent do what he/she has to do, leaving them on their own for a while).  The first half of the game, you&#146;ll be taking damage while dealing none in return; this time will be spent preparing.  This takes patience and strategy, which pays off.  While your opponent is expending Force, cards, and energy into securing themselves in their strategy, you build up and around them to control the flow of the game.  Once you have achieved your goal, you are now free to strike back at your opponent and play like the wind.  Your opponent will [hopefully] have gotten frustrated with your inactivity, and have let gaps which you can overexploit.  Working in this manner, you should be able to whittle your opponent&#146;s morale and drive down.<br>
<br>
Being The Turtle: The Mind What You Have Learned Turtle:<br>
<br>
Back in the days before Death Star II, 7 Surprise was a hot deck.  For those of you that don&#146;t know, 7 Surprise is Jedi Testing up to 5, getting a tracked 7 stacked on the test, then using Surprise Assault on all your opponent&#146;s drains to induce massive Force loss.  The way most played it was a mains-style, using the Tests in conjunction with the high Dagobah activation plus beatdown squads.  The game would start out turtled, but usually after Test 2 was out, things began to get dicey.<br>
Nowadays, Testing is hard because everyone wants to incorporate the same old strategy with new cards, but with The Way Of Things both speeding up Testing and killing the Assaults, confusion set in.  Here, you have to go turtle.  Do all your Jedi Testing without challenging your opponent at all; perhaps running Anger, Fear, Aggression constantly to hit your opponent up until you&#146;re ready to play.  The problem you run into here is direct damage, and with No Escape killing Honor Of The Jedi, this is unavoidable.  Most Dark decks will set up fast, drop hurtful cards like Search And Destroy and Come Here, You Big Coward! to get you off-base.  For you to be able to survive this, you need to pack a lot of cards that you can afford to lose early, but then get back later with retrieval.  Once Mind What You Have Learned flips, you are ready to rock and roll.  Out come the mains, tech, or what-have-you to foul your opponent&#146;s holdings, and to clear and/or control all the battleground locations on table.  After that, whatever you can do to deal damage gets done, and the losses begin to mount up to a win for you.<br>
You may find my argument to be disagreeable; if you are a regular MWYHL player, then congratulations for you discovering a method that works for you, but if not, then don&#146;t knock it until you really, truly try it.<br>
<br>
Being The Turtle: The Death Star Turtle:<br>
<br>
When A New Hope first came out, every Dark player played Commence Primary Ignition.  It was just too cool to blow planets up and force your opponent to be able to do nothing.  Guess what: it still is.  As more sets came out, CPI got lost in the shuffle, and once Special Edition came out, was forgotten (but not completely).<br>
I play CPI regularly (check out my decks titled CPI Navy v#.#), so here I know what I&#146;m talking about.  Turtling with this is easy.  Since Watch Your Step and Hidden Base mains are the most popular Light decks right now, ways of manipulating the Light Side become crucial.  With the Death Star, you have what you need.  Since most Light decks run for speed, you need some shelter from their early damage.  This is accomplished via blocking and canceling their drains using undercover spies and non-unique somethings and/or interrupts, respectively.  While the Light Side is doing its thing, you&#146;re getting out Death Star sites, Gunners, and the Superlaser.  Once armed, the Death Star roams the galaxy awaiting targets.  The first target is a Rebel Base, along with A Day Long Remembered as added punishment and hurt.  You get a big morale victory and frustrate your opponent with this.  The Death Star then continues to move along, zapping all the other planets your opponent has set foot upon.  Once your opponent is left with nothing do, they basically give up and allow you 100% free reign.  Here, you then proceed to inflict as much damage as you can, using such tech as the Dark Side version of Alderaan to drain for a large amount, direct damage like Ability, Ability, Ability, or whatever other concoction that you can sculpt to a big win in the end.<br>
<br>
Final Words:<br>
<br>
I hope that my examples were helpful in describing the turtle method.  I wish I had more to work with, but there isn&#146;t much that is workable.<br>
<br>
Closing:<br>
<br>
If you make an attempt at constructing your own turtle deck, good luck.  You must be sharp while playing it, careful not to foul up your own actions.  Once you have established mental domination over your opponent, I hope you find it as enjoyable as I have.<br>
 </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2288"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2288"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=2288" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
